Notes: These are suggested retail prices (ex-factory). Actual street prices may vary slightly by dealer or include import fees. Base Price usually means a standard grade (no engraving or basic scroll logo, standard wood). Engraving and upgrades significantly increase cost - as seen, an engraved SC3 grade can add $10k-$15k, and SCO grade (full coverage by master engraver) can add $30k+ to the base[131]. Gold inlays and sideplates push it even higher, into the $70k-$80k range for a fully decked out flagship model[117]. Essentially, one could spend from ~$15k for a plain competition Perazzi up to ~$80k for an exhibition-grade masterpiece. Most competition shooters opt for somewhere in the middle (e.g. an MX8 or HT with SC3 engraving and nice wood in the $25k-$40k range).
What's included in the price: Typically, the base price includes the gun built to your specifications with one barrel set, fixed chokes (or choice of constriction), standard stock dimensions or custom dimensions, choice of trigger type, and a factory case. Many custom options are included at no charge - for instance, you can choose any barrel length or rib height without extra fees (except some specialized ribs), get an adjustable comb installed (often at a modest extra charge or included as a "no-cost" option per promotions)[76], and select standard engraving pattern (like minimal scroll or just the Perazzi logo) at no extra cost. Extra-cost options would be: multi-chokes (adding screw-in chokes usually adds a fee, since you get a set of tubes)[132]; premium wood upgrade (SC2, SC3, etc.)[81]; engraving packages beyond basic; extra barrel sets (e.g. buying a 20ga set along with your 12ga barrels); custom finishes like receiver color plating or special coatings; and certain deluxe features (e.g. a glove grip stock might add cost for the extra labor, adjustable buttplate if desired, or things like barrel porting which is an extra service)[133]. These extras are clearly spelled out in Perazzi's price list - for example, a choke tube set might be a few hundred dollars, a selectable trigger might be a few hundred, a high-grade engraving could be tens of thousands.
Wood Grade Pricing: To illustrate, a standard Grade 1 stock is included. Upgrading to SC2 wood might add on the order of $1,000-$1,500. SC3 grade perhaps $2,000-$3,000 more than base. SCO grade (exhibition) could add $5,000 or more, depending on availability of truly exceptional blanks[81]. These are ballpark figures - the exact upcharge is often set by the factory. At a factory visit, if you hand-pick a particularly rare blank, they will quote the surcharge accordingly.
Engraving Pricing: The SC3 engraving pattern (often a fine English scroll) might add roughly $8,000-$12,000 to the price. The SCO pattern (full coverage with perhaps game scenes or deep relief scroll by a named master engraver) could be a $20,000+ upgrade. Adding gold inlay to an SCO pattern (making it "SCO Gold") further increases the price (as seen by the ~$5k jump in price list between SCO and SCO Gold)[117][134]. Sideplates (having a sideplate receiver that gives more engraving canvas) also come at a premium - an MX8 SCO sideplate is listed around $74,800 vs $52,100 for standard boxlock SCO[135]. That difference is largely engraving cost and extra work on the sideplate design. Essentially, engraving is a major factor for collectors or those wanting a functional art piece. Many shooters skip high engraving to keep costs moderate and because a heavily engraved gun might be less worry-free to use in hard competition.
Model Differences and Cost: Interestingly, models with fixed triggers (like MX12, MX2000S, HTS) are priced roughly on par or only slightly above their removable-trigger counterparts in base configuration[119][121]. The choice of removable vs fixed trigger is more about preference than cost. Barrel length or type (unsingle vs O/U vs combo) obviously affects price: Trap combos (one single + one O/U barrel) are significantly more expensive than a single gun. For example, a High Tech trap combo is around $27k base[136], whereas just the single-barrel gun was $15.9k[137]. The combo essentially adds the cost of the second barrel plus fitting. Small gauge frames (28ga or .410 on true scaled-down actions) also cost more - the price list shows an extra charge for 28/.410 on a scaled frame (~$4,380) vs making them on a 12ga frame with sub-gauge barrels (~$1,680)[31]. This reflects the additional machining for a smaller action and different ejectors, etc.
Market positioning: In the luxury shotgun world, Perazzi's pricing is competitive. They are generally more expensive than mass-produced brands like Browning or Beretta's standard line, but less expensive than British "best guns" or certain boutique Italian brands like Fabbri or Piotti (which can run $100k+). For a serious competition shooter, a Perazzi is often seen as a sound investment: it holds value well and can be rebuilt indefinitely. Used Perazzis often sell for high prices, and some limited editions even appreciate. The Blue Book of Gun Values notes that Perazzis have high resale value, especially if well-maintained[138]. The modularity means one could resell a barrel or stock separately, though ideally they are kept as a matching set.
In summary, the pricing structure has a broad range. One can enter the Perazzi world around $12k-$15k (perhaps with a basic model or a good used one) and that gun will perform identically to a $50k version in competition. The higher prices mainly buy aesthetics and personalization. Perazzi's strategy is to give the bespoke gun experience at a semi-production price - thus attracting both hard-core competitors who value function and wealthy enthusiasts who want something exclusive. The company's price lists are transparent: "Prices are intended Ex-Factory and products will be charged at the price applicable at time of delivery."[139] (i.e., if prices update during your wait, the delivery price may reflect that). This is standard for custom orders. Despite the cost, many owners feel the value is justified given the longevity and performance; a well-cared Perazzi can serve across decades of heavy use, and the intangible pride of ownership is a big part of what you pay for, aligning with the brand ethos described earlier.
Events, Community, and Legacy in the Shooting World
Perazzi's influence extends beyond just selling guns - the brand plays an active role in the shooting sports community through events, sponsorships, and an engaged owner network. The company has historically chosen prestige events and unique community-building efforts to maintain its elite image while fostering customer loyalty. Here are some key aspects of Perazzi's involvement in events and the broader community:
	o	The Perazzi Invitational: In recent marketing plans, Perazzi outlined the concept of a Perazzi Invitational - an exclusive shooting event or series reserved for those deeply aligned with the brand's values[140]. Unlike typical sponsored tournaments that are open to many, the Perazzi Invitational is envisioned as "more than an event - it's a declaration of identity", where participation is by merit and brand affinity rather than just entry fee[140]. The idea is to create a prestigious stage for top shooters (and aspiring top shooters) to compete in a setting carefully curated by Perazzi. There would be no clutter of competing logos - only Perazzi in the spotlight - reinforcing the exclusivity. While as of 2025 this Invitational is part of Perazzi's content strategy (linked with the TCN narrative arcs)[141][140], the company has a history of sponsoring unique events (see Perazzi Classic below). If launched, the Perazzi Invitational would likely be an annual championship or high-profile shoot, possibly invitational-only or with qualification through using Perazzi guns in other competitions. It exemplifies Perazzi's approach of "occupying a realm it created exclusively for those who genuinely understand greatness"[140] - in other words, making a competition itself part of the brand mystique. Keep an eye out, as this could become a reality in coming years, serving both as a competition and a marketing showcase for the Perazzi lifestyle.
	o	Grand American & ATA Events: In the American Trap community, Perazzi has long been a prominent name. From 1998 to 2005, Perazzi USA sponsored the Perazzi Classic at the Grand American (the ATA's biggest annual championship)[142]. This was a special handicap event where the top prize was often a new Perazzi shotgun, drawing huge participation. Even after 2005, Perazzi continued presence at the Grand - for example, specific events in the program are labeled "by Perazzi", such as the President Handicap (Event 16) at the 2024 Grand American[143]. This indicates Perazzi sponsors trophies or added money for certain competitions. Additionally, many ATA Hall of Famers (Ray Stafford, Dan Bonillas, etc.) are Perazzi shooters, which further cements the brand's involvement. At the Grand American venue, Perazzi traditionally has a large vendor tent where factory reps and gunsmiths provide service (often Mauro or Roberta Perazzi themselves have attended to meet customers). Perazzi honors trapshooting history too - Daniele Perazzi was inducted into the Trapshooting Hall of Fame in 2019, recognizing his contributions to the ATA sport[144][11]. The Grand America models mentioned earlier were a nod to that community. Through these engagements, Perazzi fosters a loyal following among American trap shooters, who often form a tight-knit subculture exchanging tips on Perazzi tuning and proudly displaying the Perazzi logo.
	o	International Competitions and FITASC: On the global stage, ISSF World Cups, World Championships, and Continental championships frequently see Perazzi as the most-used shotgun. While Perazzi (unlike say Beretta) doesn't plaster its logo on team uniforms due to ISSF rules, the brand quietly benefits from the visibility of winners with their guns. They sometimes host celebratory events for their medalists. In disciplines like FITASC Sporting (international sporting clays) and FITASC Compak, Perazzi shooters like George Digweed, Christophe Auvret, and others have dominated, which in turn has led Perazzi to sponsor certain international sporting events or provide demo guns at venues. In some countries, local distributors run Perazzi Grand Prix shoots - for instance, in the UK or Italy, a "Perazzi Grand Prix" might be held where only Perazzi users compete (or Perazzi provides special prizes). These are not globally publicized, but within national circuits they reinforce community. Live pigeon shoots (although now more niche due to legalities in many places) historically saw Perazzi as a sponsor at prestigious pigeon rings in Europe and South America.
	o	Perazzi Champions Network (Community Storytelling): The earlier-mentioned TCN (The Champions Network) isn't just marketing fluff - it doubles as a community-building exercise. By featuring champions' journeys and perhaps interactive content, Perazzi creates a network of shooters (pros and enthusiasts alike) who engage with the brand story. This can involve online forums, social media groups (there are unofficial but passionate Perazzi owners groups on forums and Facebook), and content sharing that binds the community. Shooters often share pictures of their custom Perazzi or post about factory visit experiences, etc., which the brand encourages. The narrative of joining the "Perazzi family" is reinforced by actual interactions: e.g. Mauro Perazzi answering customer emails personally[145], or factory smiths remembering clients by name on repeat visits. This personal touch makes owners feel part of an exclusive club.
	o	Factory Visits and Customer Events: Visiting the Perazzi factory in Botticino is almost a pilgrimage for enthusiasts. As mentioned, customers who order guns are welcomed to come for fittings and tours. The facility includes not only manufacturing but an on-site shooting range where visitors (by appointment) can shoot trial guns or their finished gun[43]. Perazzi sometimes organizes open days or special sessions for shooting clubs to visit. They also host VIP guests - for instance, during the World Shotgun Championships or World Cup events in Italy, they might host teams at the factory for a tour and dinner. These events deepen customer loyalty. The showroom at the factory is like a mini-museum and store - one can see a display of nearly every model and option (reportedly over lb1 million worth of guns on display)[146][147]. They sell merchandise like jackets, shooting vests, and accessories on site as well[146]. Another tradition: Perazzi family dinners or banquets during major shoots - in some big competitions, Perazzi sponsors a reception for all Perazzi shooters, fostering camaraderie. The brand's representatives (like Perazzi USA staff) attend many regional championships (NSCA Nationals for sporting, National Skeet Championships, etc.) with a vendor booth to provide service and showcase guns. So, the presence is felt widely even outside the Olympics.
	o	Community and Support: The network of authorized dealers and smiths also creates a community. For instance, in the UK, Perazzi's distributor (RUAG/Longthorne in recent years) has "Perazzi fitting days" where shooters can try different demo guns. In the US, some large dealers host Perazzi demo shoots - one can test fire various models side by side. Perazzi encourages this hands-on approach, knowing that the feel of the gun often sells itself. Furthermore, the Perazzi Owner's community is active online: forums like Trapshooters.com and Shotgunworld have entire subforums devoted to Perazzi maintenance, tuning, and showcasing. The company occasionally monitors these to glean feedback.
	o	Sponsored Shooters: Perazzi maintains a roster of sponsored shooters - typically the very top athletes in trap, skeet, and sporting. Unlike some companies that pay large stipends, Perazzi's support might come in the form of providing guns (often multiple guns), custom modifications, and ensuring those shooters have whatever parts or service they need immediately. Olympians like Jessica Rossi or Josip Glasnovi'c have long been associated with Perazzi. The influence of these champions trickles down to local ranges: many aspiring shooters choose Perazzi because their idols won gold with one. Perazzi often publishes interviews or tips from these champions, which is both educational and promotional.
Through all these avenues, Perazzi cultivates an image of a brand that stands with the champions and the passionate enthusiasts. They are not trying to mass-market to every shooter, but those who are serious and appreciate the legacy. The events and community efforts reinforce the notion that buying a Perazzi means joining a prestigious, yet welcoming club - you share a bond with Olympic medalists and dedicated competitors across the world. This community aspect is a powerful asset; as many will say, "Once you shoot a Perazzi and it fits, you become part of the family."
Counterfeit Warnings, Grey Market, and Service Integrity
Because Perazzi guns and parts are valuable, the company is vigilant about protecting customers from counterfeit or unauthorized items, as well as misuse of its modular system. They provide clear warnings and policies to ensure service integrity:
	o	Authenticity of Parts: Perazzi strongly advises owners to purchase parts only from authorized sources (Perazzi USA, factory, or certified dealers) to avoid counterfeit or substandard parts. There have been instances of fake Perazzi parts (such as knock-off firing pins or springs) circulating, as well as third-party "Perazzi-style" parts. These may be cheaper but can have "mixed results" in reliability[148]. Using non-genuine springs, for example, might lead to inconsistent trigger feel or breakages. Additionally, only genuine parts ensure the gun remains in original spec. The company's warranty can be voided if failures are caused by aftermarket parts. Thus, they encourage using the official parts list and even stamping certain parts with identifiable marks.
	o	Grey-Market Guns: A "grey market" Perazzi refers to one that was not imported through official channels or is built from mismatched components. Perazzi USA is the sole importer for the U.S.[149], and similarly each country has an official agent. Guns obtained outside these channels might not carry warranty or service support. Perazzi cautions buyers to be wary of deals "too good to be true" from non-official sellers. Each Perazzi has a serial number that the company can trace to an original sale - warranty service may be refused on guns that bypassed authorized import. More subtly, Perazzi warns that some gunsmiths have built "parts guns" by combining actions and barrels from different Perazzis (because parts are interchangeable to a degree). While the fit may seem okay, these franken-guns can have improper lug engagement or trigger timing issues. Mixing serial-numbered components without proper factory fitting can compromise safety. For example, dropping an older MX8 barrel onto a newer MX8 action might lock up, but the headspace could be off or the ejectors mis-time. Perazzi's stance: always have a qualified smith fit any new barrel to your action and check headspace and point of impact. They serialize barrels, receivers, forends as matched sets at the factory for a reason.
	o	Interchanging Trigger Groups: One unique aspect is that any Perazzi drop-out trigger group will physically lock into any Perazzi receiver of the same type. This interchangeability is helpful in a pinch (e.g., borrowing a friend's trigger if yours breaks in a competition). However, Perazzi cautions that triggers "wear into" their receivers over time. Constant swapping of trigger groups between guns can cause uneven wear on sears or the safety linkage. Also, trigger pulls might vary if a trigger unit is put in a different gun due to minor differences in tolerances. The company line is: it's fine to use a spare trigger in an emergency, but for regular use, each action should have a trigger tuned to it. If you buy a second-hand trigger group, have a smith check its sear engagement in your receiver.
	o	Aftermarket Modifications: Perazzi shotguns are sometimes modified by independent gunsmiths - e.g. adding custom porting, recoil reducers, third-party adjustable comb hardware, or even decorative modifications. While owners are free to customize, Perazzi issues service disclaimers that such modifications can void warranties or future factory service. For instance, if barrels are ported by someone else and later develop a problem, Perazzi may decline to service that barrel (since the integrity was altered). The same goes for lengthening forcing cones, adjusting trigger pulls outside of spec, etc. They caution that any non-factory alteration is at the owner's risk. In particular, converting to release triggers should be done by known experts - Perazzi won't do it at the factory, but they tacitly allow it via recognized specialists. If a release trigger causes an issue, the factory won't cover it.
	o	Counterfeit Guns: Full-on counterfeit Perazzi guns are rare, but not impossible. There have been unverified reports of knock-off copies appearing in places with less regulation. To address this, Perazzi serializes every receiver and barrel and keeps records. A genuine Perazzi will also have proof marks from the Italian proof house in Gardone. The company can authenticate a gun if there's doubt. They also incorporate subtle features in the engraving of logos and numbering that are hard to duplicate. Prospective buyers are advised to purchase through reputable channels to avoid any risk of getting a fake.
	o	Serial Number Integrity: Perazzi's policy is that barrels, receivers, and forends with different serials should only be paired by the factory or authorized agents. While many Perazzi parts can be fitted across guns, doing so might create an unsafe condition if not properly headspaced or if the locking bolt engagement isn't correct. The factory sometimes fits extra barrels to an action (those will bear the same serial with an added suffix mark), but they discourage ad-hoc swapping. They have even printed warnings that using mismatched components "is not recommended and voids any responsibility of the manufacturer." Essentially, if you mix and match and something fails, that's on you. This is especially relevant with trigger groups: older models had slight differences in the interceptor sear design; jamming the wrong generation trigger in could cause doubling or failure to fire. Always consult with Perazzi experts when interchanging parts.
	o	Service by Qualified Personnel: To maintain service integrity, Perazzi trains or authorizes certain gunsmiths. In the U.S., Giacomo Arrighini was the legendary factory-trained smith; others like Lucio Sosta, Doug Gray, etc., are known for Perazzi work. The company's message: these guns are finely fitted, so don't let an amateur hone sears or "" (tinker) with the mechanism. During the warranty period, stick to factory service. After that, use known experts or send it to the factory for any major work (many do send guns to Italy for full refurbishment after years of use). The factory offers full restoration services - reblueing barrels, refinishing wood, recutting checkering, etc., which can make a well-used Perazzi look near-new again. They issue service disclaimers that any gun that's been materially altered by others may be refused for factory service, or they will charge to replace non-factory parts back to original spec. It's a protective stance to ensure quality control.
	o	Grey Import Warnings: Another aspect of grey market is pricing - if someone offers a "new Perazzi" well below list price, it might be an unofficial import (or even stolen). The advice is to buy from the network of authorized dealers to ensure you get the warranty card and proper support. Perazzi USA in Azusa often knows the background of each serial number imported; if you inquire with them about a used gun's serial, they can sometimes confirm its history.
In summary, Perazzi encourages owners to treat their shotgun as the precision instrument it is: use the right parts, don't cut corners on service, and maintain the original integrity. These guns hold their value and performance when properly cared for. The company's warnings about counterfeit/grey products and unauthorized mods are there to protect both the shooter's safety and the brand's reputation. And indeed, part of owning a Perazzi "the right way" is the peace of mind that you have factory-level support and a community of experts to help keep your gun in top condition. As Perazzi positions itself as a lifelong investment, following their guidelines on parts and service ensures your Perazzi will continue to perform for generations - living up to that legendary legacy it carries.

